Watching prices and flow of used M3 on TSLA CH site gives a quasi-real-time idea of the competitive situation.

Tracking used cars is easier than new inventory, as $TSLA shows real VIN i/o placeholder VIN for new cars that often change just to confuse folks like ev-cpo and me.

Quite a few of us are convinced that $TSLA will have to cut prices significantly if it wants to maintain yearly volume at 0.5M let alone increase it to 0.8M.

February looks *really* weak. 

🇨🇭 market share for (JAN+FEB) set to be < 10% of BEV (compared to 30% for all of 2021).

I don’t believe that is the case though. 

There really is no good explanation for $TSLA and Autoscout to be sitting on so much inventory at this stage. 

Inventory that is clearly not moving at current prices.

It is much worse compared to previous quarters.

Bulls might argue that most cars on the RORO for 🇪🇺 are built-to-order, secured by down payment many weeks ago. 

Those cars need not show up on the $TSLA 🇨🇭site ever. In that case what is visible on the website could be insignificant compared to total order BTO order flow.

Remember: $TSLA 🇨🇭also applies discounts to *new* cars, by labeling them as “demonstration model”. 

Today 14 out of 93 *new* M3 in 🇨🇭 are *demo* and have a discount ranging from 2 to 9%.

Price setting of used $TSLA M3 cars in 🇨🇭has been highly erratic of late.

In below graph each color line represents one VIN. 18 cars are shown.

The dotted lines span days while a particular VIN was hidden on the $TSLA 🇨🇭site. https://t.co/rifY3uUTnT
